@flexiarg t3/intervention-triad
@title Intervention Triad
@sigils [🔧/入]
@audience programme-designers, curriculum-leads, trainers
@tone formal-analytic
@style design-pattern
@part Open Research Training
@up t3/transformation-space
@see t3/expectation-scaffold, t3/adaptive-delivery-spine, t3/living-materials-stewardship
@next t3/architectural-pair
@length 180-260
@allow-new-claims false

! conclusion:
  Improving the training input — its clarity, structure, and maintenance — reduces confusion, overload, and rework at the point of delivery, but these intervention-level improvements are necessary, not sufficient, for normalisation; a well-designed input delivered into an unreceptive institutional environment still fails to embed.

  + context: Programme evaluation typically focuses on improving the training input; these three patterns capture the intervention-level conditions that the programme can directly control.
  + if: You want training inputs to be clear, usable, and maintainable across diverse institutional contexts.
  + however: Even well-designed inputs fail to normalise when the institutional architecture cannot receive them; intervention-level improvements are necessary but not sufficient.
  + then: Ensure the intervention triad is in place — clear expectations, adaptive structure, and maintained materials — while recognising that these address the input, not the transformation space.
  + because: The triad reduces friction at the point of delivery; without it, trainers waste effort on ambiguity, overload, and content drift, leaving no capacity for the architectural work that sustains practice.
      + mechanism: Clarity, modularity, and maintenance free trainer cognitive resources for the harder work of institutional embedding.
      + counterfactual: If the intervention triad is absent, trainers exhaust themselves on input-level problems and never reach architectural engagement.
      + applies-when: Multiple trainers deliver across institutions with varying local conditions.
      + does-not-apply: A single trainer with a fixed audience and stable, well-maintained content.
      + signals: Trainers report confusion about requirements, overstuffed sessions, or outdated materials.
      + evidence: Patterns 1-3 each supported by 3+ transcript sources across all four focus groups; COM-B items on psychological capability (M=4.85) and institutional resource appropriateness (M=3.78) corroborate.
  + next-steps:
      - Audit the programme against each pattern in the triad.
      - Address intervention-level gaps before expecting architecture-level engagement.
      - Document which intervention-level improvements are within programme control versus requiring institutional action.
  + governance:
      - practice: review intervention triad coverage before each cohort intake.
      - metric: trainer-reported clarity, session time compliance, and materials currency.
